SPEAKER 1: So one
of the questions

01:04:35.640 --> 01:04:38.330
was regarding a company
which in your blog posts

01:04:38.330 --> 01:04:41.150
you call the "Field
of Dreams" company.

01:04:41.150 --> 01:04:43.920
The question is,
growing revenues,

01:04:43.920 --> 01:04:46.920
the earnings are maybe
shown, not shown,

01:04:46.920 --> 01:04:48.780
but the cash flows are there.

01:04:48.780 --> 01:04:50.310
And a lot of that
is still driven

01:04:50.310 --> 01:04:52.390
by changes in working capital.

01:04:52.390 --> 01:04:55.920
So for those of you who don't
know, I'm talking about Amazon.

01:04:55.920 --> 01:04:58.439
The question is, how do you
look at a company like that

01:04:58.439 --> 01:04:59.730
and what do you think about it?

01:04:59.730 --> 01:05:01.160
ASWATH DAMODARAN: You know I
call it the "Field of Dreams"

01:05:01.160 --> 01:05:02.130
company, right?

01:05:02.130 --> 01:05:03.660
Seen "Field of Dreams?"

01:05:03.660 --> 01:05:06.750
Kevin Costner builds
this baseball field

01:05:06.750 --> 01:05:08.402
in the middle of
nowhere and people

01:05:08.402 --> 01:05:09.610
ask him, what are you, crazy?

01:05:09.610 --> 01:05:12.235
Why are you building a baseball
field in the middle of nowhere?

01:05:12.235 --> 01:05:16.770
And remember what he said, if
I build it, they will come.

01:05:16.770 --> 01:05:17.670
That to me is--

01:05:17.670 --> 01:05:20.460
when I think about Amazon,
that is the message

01:05:20.460 --> 01:05:23.880
that Jeff Bezos has been
sending right from day one.

01:05:23.880 --> 01:05:26.640
If you get a chance,
go check out the letter

01:05:26.640 --> 01:05:29.937
that Jeff wrote
about Amazon in 1997.

01:05:29.937 --> 01:05:31.020
You know where I found it?

01:05:31.020 --> 01:05:34.280
I found it in Google search,
so you can find it, too.

01:05:34.280 --> 01:05:36.140
It's actually an
incredible letter

01:05:36.140 --> 01:05:38.870
because it lays out what he
was going to do at Amazon.

01:05:38.870 --> 01:05:43.140
He said, at Amazon we're
going to go for revenues first

01:05:43.140 --> 01:05:45.570
and then after we've
built the revenues,

01:05:45.570 --> 01:05:48.220
they will come, the profits.

01:05:48.220 --> 01:05:50.650
That's the story
told in '97 and he's

01:05:50.650 --> 01:05:52.510
told the same
story for 20 years.

01:05:52.510 --> 01:05:55.009
And he's acted consistently
with that story.

01:05:55.009 --> 01:05:56.800
You know what I mean
by acted consistently?

01:05:56.800 --> 01:06:00.090
How many people here
have Amazon Prime?

01:06:00.090 --> 01:06:02.360
What do you pay for it?

01:06:02.360 --> 01:06:03.410
$99.

01:06:03.410 --> 01:06:07.010
Do you know what it costs Amazon
to service every Prime member?

01:06:07.010 --> 01:06:09.170
About $400.

01:06:09.170 --> 01:06:11.270
That's crazy, why
would you do that?

01:06:11.270 --> 01:06:13.760
If you build it, they will come.

01:06:13.760 --> 01:06:15.470
What is he building
with Amazon Prime?

01:06:15.470 --> 01:06:17.870
He's building this
block of consumers

01:06:17.870 --> 01:06:20.300
who are addicted
to Amazon, for lack

01:06:20.300 --> 01:06:23.840
of a better word, Who don't even
know what a retail store looks

01:06:23.840 --> 01:06:25.610
like anymore.

01:06:25.610 --> 01:06:29.220
And one of these days,
he's coming for you.

01:06:29.220 --> 01:06:31.190
So don't be surprised
if a third nine pops up

01:06:31.190 --> 01:06:34.490
after the first two nines and
you have nothing you can do,

01:06:34.490 --> 01:06:36.410
because where are
you going to go?

01:06:36.410 --> 01:06:38.810
Everything else will be
out of business by then.

01:06:38.810 --> 01:06:41.090
So the conspiratorial
view about Amazon

01:06:41.090 --> 01:06:43.610
is he's building a business
where ultimately, he's

01:06:43.610 --> 01:06:45.020
going to get you.

01:06:45.020 --> 01:06:50.740
And that explains the
$700, $800, $900 per share.

01:06:50.740 --> 01:06:52.840
The problem there is
it is a business where

01:06:52.840 --> 01:06:55.996
keeping newcomers out, new
ways of doing business,

01:06:55.996 --> 01:06:57.120
is going to be tough to do.

01:06:57.120 --> 01:06:59.376
So the challenge here is
what if that doesn't happen?

01:06:59.376 --> 01:07:01.000
Well, you could end
up growing revenues

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:03.490
and never being able
to deliver the profits.

01:07:03.490 --> 01:07:07.090
So it's, again, a
fascinating case study of how

01:07:07.090 --> 01:07:09.280
if you can tell a
consistent story.

01:07:09.280 --> 01:07:11.380
Because people often say,
markets are short-term.

01:07:11.380 --> 01:07:14.060
You heard that probably
in Silicon Valley.

01:07:14.060 --> 01:07:17.510
What short-term market would
let a company go for 20 years

01:07:17.510 --> 01:07:22.100
without making a profit and keep
pushing up their market cap?

01:07:22.100 --> 01:07:24.250
To me Amazon is the
perfect counter-example

01:07:24.250 --> 01:07:26.540
of if you can tell
a consistent story,

01:07:26.540 --> 01:07:29.390
markets will cut you a
heck of a lot of slack.

01:07:29.390 --> 01:07:31.580
You know why they don't
do it for most companies?

01:07:31.580 --> 01:07:34.190
Because the story keeps
changing every year.

01:07:34.190 --> 01:07:37.040
The top management is incapable
of telling the same story

01:07:37.040 --> 01:07:40.710
over time and then the market
says, we don't trust you.

01:07:40.710 --> 01:07:43.055
So the other lesson that I
think you get out of Amazon

01:07:43.055 --> 01:07:44.430
is if you're
building a business,

01:07:44.430 --> 01:07:47.380
you're telling a story, don't
keep swinging like a weather

01:07:47.380 --> 01:07:49.440
vane to whatever works.

01:07:49.440 --> 01:07:51.660
You have to have a
consistent story,

01:07:51.660 --> 01:07:53.820
you have to act consistently
with that story.

01:07:53.820 --> 01:07:57.180
And you'll be surprised
at how much slack you

01:07:57.180 --> 01:07:59.672
get cut because of that.

01:07:59.672 --> 01:08:02.130
