01:09:26.009 --> 01:09:27.550
AUDIENCE: So there
are some companies

01:09:27.550 --> 01:09:29.479
that need external
capital at the beginning,

01:09:29.479 --> 01:09:30.850
like Tesla, right?

01:09:30.850 --> 01:09:32.710
For those companies,
they're actually

01:09:32.710 --> 01:09:36.370
more valuable if they are priced
higher because the capital will

01:09:36.370 --> 01:09:38.359
be very low, right?

01:09:38.359 --> 01:09:39.800
If they are priced
at $2 trillion,

01:09:39.800 --> 01:09:41.760
again, issue the
stocks very cheaply

01:09:41.760 --> 01:09:44.250
and they get any
money they want.

01:09:44.250 --> 01:09:47.500
And it also applies to real
state investment trusts.

01:09:47.500 --> 01:09:49.654
How do you put that
in your valuation?

01:09:49.654 --> 01:09:50.529
ASWATH DAMODARAN: OK.

01:09:50.529 --> 01:09:52.899
The first thing to remember
is you don't set the price,

01:09:52.899 --> 01:09:53.640
the market does.

01:09:53.640 --> 01:09:56.110
So if you can get them to
give you a high pricing,

01:09:56.110 --> 01:09:58.400
it does make your life easier.

01:09:58.400 --> 01:10:01.045
I mean, you hear this word
cash burn thrown around Silicon

01:10:01.045 --> 01:10:02.170
Valley all the time, right?

01:10:02.170 --> 01:10:04.419
Cash burn basically means
you have negative cash flows

01:10:04.419 --> 01:10:06.610
up front because you need
that cash flow to grow.

01:10:06.610 --> 01:10:09.520
And you have cash burn, you need
capital to cover the cash flow.

01:10:09.520 --> 01:10:11.840
You can't survive as a company.

01:10:11.840 --> 01:10:13.615
And if you're priced
high, the advantage

01:10:13.615 --> 01:10:18.020
is you can raise that capital
at a very advantageous price.

01:10:18.020 --> 01:10:20.217
So here is, in fact,
what it plays out as.

01:10:20.217 --> 01:10:22.300
For these companies, there's
actually an incentive

01:10:22.300 --> 01:10:24.250
to tell really,
really big stories

01:10:24.250 --> 01:10:26.680
up front, right, because big
stories get the big prices.

01:10:26.680 --> 01:10:29.470
The pricing allows you
then to cover the capital.

01:10:29.470 --> 01:10:31.169
There will be a
letdown at some point

01:10:31.169 --> 01:10:33.460
because people are going to
say, well, that story never

01:10:33.460 --> 01:10:36.120
was going to work.

01:10:36.120 --> 01:10:39.230
And then you get all kinds
of disappointment kicking in.

01:10:39.230 --> 01:10:40.850
I might be hitting
too close to home,

01:10:40.850 --> 01:10:43.872
but anybody ever
hear of Juicera?

01:10:43.872 --> 01:10:45.580
I've been reading the
story about Juicera

01:10:45.580 --> 01:10:48.210
and I said, what kind of story
would you need to tell me

01:10:48.210 --> 01:10:49.590
for me to invest in it?

01:10:49.590 --> 01:10:54.180
How many people would pay
$400 for a juicer that's--

01:10:54.180 --> 01:10:56.856
I mean, it's a
very small market.

01:10:56.856 --> 01:10:58.230
So if you were
telling that story

01:10:58.230 --> 01:11:01.150
and I was assuming a market of
50 million Americans buying,

01:11:01.150 --> 01:11:03.060
it's a story that doesn't fly.

01:11:03.060 --> 01:11:06.750
But if you could push the story
bigger, you'd push pricing up.

01:11:06.750 --> 01:11:10.600
It allows you to raise capital
to cover your cash burn needs.

01:11:10.600 --> 01:11:12.330
So that's something to remember.

01:11:12.330 --> 01:11:15.050
I don't think that's
Elon Musk's rationale.

01:11:15.050 --> 01:11:18.280
I think he just likes
telling really big stories

01:11:18.280 --> 01:11:19.890
and making them
bigger over time.

01:11:19.890 --> 01:11:24.699
But I think for some start-ups,
I think part of this is a game.

01:11:24.699 --> 01:11:27.240
If you can push your pricing
up, it actually makes it easier.

01:11:27.240 --> 01:11:29.490
It greases the skids
for you while you have

01:11:29.490 --> 01:11:31.410
those early years of cash burn.

01:11:31.410 --> 01:11:33.240
