01:11:57.360 --> 01:12:00.480
ASWATH DAMODARAN: As I
said, one of the things

01:12:00.480 --> 01:12:03.540
I find that gets in the
way of good investing

01:12:03.540 --> 01:12:06.360
is I tell people the
three words that you

01:12:06.360 --> 01:12:12.240
need to be able to say openly
in investing is, I was wrong.

01:12:12.240 --> 01:12:15.150
Because once you say that, it
frees you from your own story.

01:12:15.150 --> 01:12:17.310
Because as long as you're
not willing to say that,

01:12:17.310 --> 01:12:19.018
you're going to find
ways to kind of take

01:12:19.018 --> 01:12:21.720
your old story that it's
not wrong, this part of it--

01:12:21.720 --> 01:12:25.140
it's somebody else's fault.
I have absolutely no qualms

01:12:25.140 --> 01:12:27.660
about accepting the
fact that I'm wrong

01:12:27.660 --> 01:12:31.410
and I'm horribly wrong
sometimes and it's not my fault.

01:12:31.410 --> 01:12:33.656
That's what allows me
to get away with it.

01:12:33.656 --> 01:12:35.155
It's not my fault
in the sense there

01:12:35.155 --> 01:12:38.210
are things happening around
that I really can't control.

01:12:38.210 --> 01:12:40.960
So when I'm wrong, I have to
look at what portion of it

01:12:40.960 --> 01:12:44.980
was my fault and what portion
of it is out of my control.

01:12:44.980 --> 01:12:47.200
With Valle, here's
what happened.

01:12:47.200 --> 01:12:49.510
I bought Valle and
Brazil went to hell

01:12:49.510 --> 01:12:53.030
in a handbasket in the
year after I bought Valle.

01:12:53.030 --> 01:12:54.530
You say, why didn't
he predict that?

01:12:54.530 --> 01:12:56.090
If I had been able
to predict it,

01:12:56.090 --> 01:12:57.980
there were a lot easier
ways to make money

01:12:57.980 --> 01:12:59.440
than to go out and buy--

01:12:59.440 --> 01:13:02.870
I could have sold short
in Brazilian bonds.

01:13:02.870 --> 01:13:04.080
It was out of mind control.

01:13:04.080 --> 01:13:07.020
I call this the karmic
moment in investing.

01:13:07.020 --> 01:13:08.419
You've heard of karma, right?

01:13:08.419 --> 01:13:10.460
Basically, karma means
there are some things that

01:13:10.460 --> 01:13:12.950
are going to happen, nothing
that you and I can do

01:13:12.950 --> 01:13:14.490
can change that.

01:13:14.490 --> 01:13:17.802
You've got to accept that
on Valle I was wrong,

01:13:17.802 --> 01:13:19.760
but there's nothing I
could have done about it.

01:13:19.760 --> 01:13:23.660
With Valeant I was wrong
and it was partly my fault.

01:13:23.660 --> 01:13:25.460
And here's what I
missed in Valeant.

01:13:25.460 --> 01:13:27.251
For those of you not
familiar with Valeant,

01:13:27.251 --> 01:13:30.350
Valeant built its reputation
as an uncommon pharmaceutical

01:13:30.350 --> 01:13:34.130
company by going out and
acquiring other drug companies

01:13:34.130 --> 01:13:38.180
and doing something that
is morally and ethically

01:13:38.180 --> 01:13:38.750
questionable.

01:13:38.750 --> 01:13:43.357
They would take underpriced
drugs and reprice them.

01:13:43.357 --> 01:13:44.690
You know what that means, right?

01:13:44.690 --> 01:13:46.500
So you're a company
which is at a--

01:13:46.500 --> 01:13:49.172
let's say you're heart
drug that's been around,

01:13:49.172 --> 01:13:50.630
it's been patented
for eight years.

01:13:50.630 --> 01:13:52.960
They're charging $50 a dose.

01:13:52.960 --> 01:13:55.880
It serves only
like 7,000 people.

01:13:55.880 --> 01:13:58.240
And Valeant said, those
people will pay $5,000.

01:13:58.240 --> 01:14:00.199
They need it to live.

01:14:00.199 --> 01:14:00.990
They raised prices.

01:14:00.990 --> 01:14:02.910
They did incredibly
well for a period.

01:14:02.910 --> 01:14:06.630
But that story was a story that
worked only as long as they

01:14:06.630 --> 01:14:07.980
stayed under the radar, right?

01:14:07.980 --> 01:14:10.022
Because this is
not exactly a story

01:14:10.022 --> 01:14:11.230
you're going to tell openly--

01:14:11.230 --> 01:14:13.063
we buy other companies,
we take their drugs,

01:14:13.063 --> 01:14:17.730
we increase the price
50% or 500% or 5000%.

01:14:17.730 --> 01:14:19.200
So when Valeant
came apart, it was

01:14:19.200 --> 01:14:20.760
because they got too ambitious.

01:14:20.760 --> 01:14:21.630
They got too big.

01:14:21.630 --> 01:14:23.790
They bought Salix, an
$18 billion company.

01:14:23.790 --> 01:14:26.550
When they tried to raise
the price of the drugs,

01:14:26.550 --> 01:14:27.900
people noticed.

01:14:27.900 --> 01:14:30.520
And the minute that happened,
the whole company unraveled.

01:14:30.520 --> 01:14:34.020
It dropped from
$200 down to $32.

01:14:34.020 --> 01:14:35.820
And I bought it at
$32 saying, look,

01:14:35.820 --> 01:14:37.570
there's still enough
value in the company.

01:14:37.570 --> 01:14:40.830
You know what I missed
is this company did so

01:14:40.830 --> 01:14:42.460
much damage to its reputation.

01:14:42.460 --> 01:14:44.085
We talk about corporate
sustainability.

01:14:44.085 --> 01:14:47.460
It taught me a lesson about
why corporate sustainability

01:14:47.460 --> 01:14:48.510
has a place in Valeant.

01:14:48.510 --> 01:14:50.550
They had done so much
damage to their reputation

01:14:50.550 --> 01:14:52.094
that nobody trusted them.

01:14:52.094 --> 01:14:53.760
Because I assumed
that they would become

01:14:53.760 --> 01:14:55.467
an old fashioned drug company.

01:14:55.467 --> 01:14:57.300
But to become an old
fashioned drug company,

01:14:57.300 --> 01:14:57.780
what do you have to do?

01:14:57.780 --> 01:14:59.130
You have to build
an R&amp;D department,

01:14:59.130 --> 01:15:00.379
you've got to hire scientists.

01:15:00.379 --> 01:15:01.530
Let me ask you a question.

01:15:01.530 --> 01:15:02.970
You're a scientist, I'm Valeant.

01:15:02.970 --> 01:15:05.580
I come and say, do you
want a job at Valeant?

01:15:05.580 --> 01:15:06.750
What's your reaction?

01:15:06.750 --> 01:15:09.167
I've heard about you guys,
I'm not coming there.

01:15:09.167 --> 01:15:11.250
So they're having trouble
building their business.

01:15:11.250 --> 01:15:14.070
They try to sell a
portion of the business.

01:15:14.070 --> 01:15:16.810
I'm Valeant, I try to sell a
portion of my business to you.

01:15:16.810 --> 01:15:17.899
What's your reaction?

01:15:17.899 --> 01:15:18.690
You guys are liars.

01:15:18.690 --> 01:15:20.640
I don't trust anything you do.

01:15:20.640 --> 01:15:22.770
So what I missed in
the case of Valeant

01:15:22.770 --> 01:15:25.830
is the damage that they had
done to their reputation that

01:15:25.830 --> 01:15:29.470
makes it almost impossible for
them to be a going concern.

01:15:29.470 --> 01:15:33.630
That damage cost me, what, 60%
of my investment in Valeant.

01:15:33.630 --> 01:15:36.090
But it's a lesson that
I can use when I think

01:15:36.090 --> 01:15:37.390
about other damaged companies.

01:15:37.390 --> 01:15:39.790
So would I buy United
after the billion dollars?

01:15:39.790 --> 01:15:40.300
Maybe.

01:15:40.300 --> 01:15:40.740
Here's why.

01:15:40.740 --> 01:15:42.310
It's a damaged company,
but it's in a business

01:15:42.310 --> 01:15:42.950
where they're all damaged.

01:15:42.950 --> 01:15:45.170
There but for the grace
of God goes Delta, right?

01:15:45.170 --> 01:15:48.030
Don't assume that Delta would
not have dragged you off.

01:15:48.030 --> 01:15:51.780
Maybe they'd have dragged you
off a little more gently, OK?

01:15:51.780 --> 01:15:54.870
This is a business-- and that's
why I bought Volkswagen after

01:15:54.870 --> 01:15:55.650
the--

01:15:55.650 --> 01:15:58.060
because I looked at
Volkswagen and said, hey,

01:15:58.060 --> 01:16:00.270
do you think only
Volkswagen does this stuff?

01:16:00.270 --> 01:16:01.620
They all do it.

01:16:01.620 --> 01:16:04.170
You've knocked down the
value of Volkswagen 24%.

01:16:04.170 --> 01:16:06.995
So it's a game
I've played before.

01:16:06.995 --> 01:16:08.370
But in the case
of Valeant, I got

01:16:08.370 --> 01:16:10.500
this warning sign of
sometimes a company

01:16:10.500 --> 01:16:15.240
can step across the line so
much that coming back over

01:16:15.240 --> 01:16:18.360
is going to be
really tough to do.

01:16:18.360 --> 01:16:20.967
And the other thing
is a mistake will

01:16:20.967 --> 01:16:23.550
cost you a lot less if you don't
have half your money invested

01:16:23.550 --> 01:16:24.780
in the mistake.

01:16:24.780 --> 01:16:28.370
So this is actually a pushback
against what you sometimes

01:16:28.370 --> 01:16:31.770
hear from value investors which
is don't spread their bets,

01:16:31.770 --> 01:16:33.570
buy four great companies.

01:16:33.570 --> 01:16:35.760
I have never
believed that advice.

01:16:35.760 --> 01:16:37.770
That's hubris to think
that somehow you've

01:16:37.770 --> 01:16:41.040
got these four winners forever.

01:16:41.040 --> 01:16:45.720
So to me, the reason I keep
any investment I make at 10%

01:16:45.720 --> 01:16:48.660
or below my portfolio is because
I know I can make mistakes

01:16:48.660 --> 01:16:49.952
and I have to be aware of that.

01:16:49.952 --> 01:16:52.035
SPEAKER 1: What does your
typical positions always

01:16:52.035 --> 01:16:52.590
look like?

01:16:52.590 --> 01:16:55.080
ASWATH DAMODARAN: I would
say on entry about 5%.

01:16:55.080 --> 01:16:57.960
If it does well, if will get
to 10%; if it does badly,

01:16:57.960 --> 01:17:01.270
it takes care of itself, it
goes away from my portfolio.

01:17:01.270 --> 01:17:04.720
So Valeant is no longer
5% of my portfolio.

01:17:04.720 --> 01:17:07.890
So it's really the stocks that
do well that I have to nurture.

01:17:07.890 --> 01:17:09.960
And in fact, with
Apple this will

01:17:09.960 --> 01:17:15.330
played out over a 15-year period
because I bought Apple in 1998

01:17:15.330 --> 01:17:18.040
and I bought it as a
charitable contribution.

01:17:18.040 --> 01:17:19.290
Because I loved Apple so much.

01:17:19.290 --> 01:17:21.081
It looked like it was
going out of business

01:17:21.081 --> 01:17:23.550
and this was going to be
my final contribution,

01:17:23.550 --> 01:17:25.050
look how much I loved you.

01:17:25.050 --> 01:17:26.334
Here, take the $14.

01:17:26.334 --> 01:17:28.500
It turned out to be the
best investment I ever made.

01:17:28.500 --> 01:17:30.692
Sometimes shows you that
your best investments don't

01:17:30.692 --> 01:17:32.400
come from all your
intrinsic value stuff,

01:17:32.400 --> 01:17:34.770
it comes from your
charitable contribution.

01:17:34.770 --> 01:17:36.660
The problem with
Apple is did so well

01:17:36.660 --> 01:17:39.690
that it kept pushing
into that 10%.

01:17:39.690 --> 01:17:42.867
I left about half
the profits I'd

01:17:42.867 --> 01:17:45.450
have made on Apple on the table
because I had to keep selling.

01:17:45.450 --> 01:17:48.060
And I have no
regrets for doing it

01:17:48.060 --> 01:17:51.270
because that's what I need
to do to be disciplined.

01:17:51.270 --> 01:17:54.110
And one of the things
I've discovered is if I--

01:17:54.110 --> 01:17:55.670
the way I do this
is I automate it.

01:17:55.670 --> 01:17:57.720
Do you know what I
mean by automate it?

01:17:57.720 --> 01:17:59.820
I have limit sells on
every single investment

01:17:59.820 --> 01:18:03.340
in my portfolio that I have
put in before it happens.

01:18:03.340 --> 01:18:05.670
Because if I wait for it
to happen and then I say,

01:18:05.670 --> 01:18:09.390
should I sell it now, I find
delusional ways of saying,

01:18:09.390 --> 01:18:11.250
this time is
different, this stock

01:18:11.250 --> 01:18:12.790
is going to keep going up.

01:18:12.790 --> 01:18:15.750
So sometimes lots
of time you've got

01:18:15.750 --> 01:18:18.720
to realize that you
can't trust yourself.

01:18:18.720 --> 01:18:20.880
You essentially have
to automate the process

01:18:20.880 --> 01:18:22.089
to take it out of your hands.

01:18:22.089 --> 01:18:24.254
SPEAKER 1: So we were talking
about your limit order

01:18:24.254 --> 01:18:25.890
on Apple before,
and I think it would

01:18:25.890 --> 01:18:27.540
be nice for the
audience to maybe share

01:18:27.540 --> 01:18:29.050
some of that conversation.

01:18:29.050 --> 01:18:31.050
But I found it very interesting.

01:18:31.050 --> 01:18:34.020
So you had an estimate
of intrinsic value

01:18:34.020 --> 01:18:38.400
and once it hit, the limit
order executed for Apple.

01:18:38.400 --> 01:18:41.310
My question to you
was, if the price then

01:18:41.310 --> 01:18:43.630
goes below that price, are
you going to buy again?

01:18:43.630 --> 01:18:45.690
In other words, how do
you think or quantify

01:18:45.690 --> 01:18:48.210
the margin of safety and
how do you differentiate

01:18:48.210 --> 01:18:49.955
buying and selling?

01:18:49.955 --> 01:18:52.080
ASWATH DAMODARAN: When I
bought Apple, I got lucky.

01:18:52.080 --> 01:18:55.620
I bought Apple at $94, I
put a limit sell at $140,

01:18:55.620 --> 01:18:58.069
and it executed so Apple
is out of my portfolio.

01:18:58.069 --> 01:18:59.610
I've bought Apple
four times and I've

01:18:59.610 --> 01:19:01.630
sold Apple four times
in the last six years.

01:19:01.630 --> 01:19:02.130
Why?

01:19:02.130 --> 01:19:04.030
Because my value stayed
stable, but here's

01:19:04.030 --> 01:19:05.290
what happens to Apple.

01:19:05.290 --> 01:19:09.046
A new iPhone comes out, revenues
jump 8%, people start dancing

01:19:09.046 --> 01:19:09.670
in the streets.

01:19:09.670 --> 01:19:11.170
It's a growth company again.

01:19:11.170 --> 01:19:13.420
They push up the price
too much and then

01:19:13.420 --> 01:19:15.100
four quarters later,
their revenues

01:19:15.100 --> 01:19:17.050
drop because the iPhone
is aging and people

01:19:17.050 --> 01:19:19.452
are convinced that this is
the end, they sell Apple off.

01:19:19.452 --> 01:19:21.160
So it's almost like
your taking advantage

01:19:21.160 --> 01:19:24.780
of a manic depressive, which
is what the market is-- manic,

01:19:24.780 --> 01:19:28.900
I sell to it, and it's
depressed, I buy from it.

01:19:28.900 --> 01:19:30.700
My rule of thumb,
though, in investing

01:19:30.700 --> 01:19:34.150
is I want to buy when I feel
that a stock is undervalued.

01:19:34.150 --> 01:19:37.480
And when I value a stock, I
come up with a point estimate.

01:19:37.480 --> 01:19:39.280
But that's, again,
hubris, right?

01:19:39.280 --> 01:19:40.930
Because I made assumptions.

01:19:40.930 --> 01:19:42.969
The assumptions were
revenues will grow 7%.

01:19:42.969 --> 01:19:45.010
But if you push me, I'd
say, well, you know what?

01:19:45.010 --> 01:19:47.680
They probably can grow 5% to 9%.

01:19:47.680 --> 01:19:49.990
So over the last few
years, I've taken

01:19:49.990 --> 01:19:52.480
to using Monte Carlo
simulations in my valuation,

01:19:52.480 --> 01:19:56.110
partly because it forces me to
be honest about how uncertain I

01:19:56.110 --> 01:20:00.460
am and then it forces me to be
specific about how uncertain I

01:20:00.460 --> 01:20:01.750
am.

01:20:01.750 --> 01:20:04.530
And I get a
distribution of value,

01:20:04.530 --> 01:20:07.210
that becomes my basis
for deciding when to buy.

01:20:07.210 --> 01:20:09.970
So I'm not going to buy
Apple when it drops to $139.

01:20:09.970 --> 01:20:10.870
My value is $140.

01:20:10.870 --> 01:20:13.155
It dropping to $139,
I'm still with--

01:20:13.155 --> 01:20:14.530
if you look at
this distribution,

01:20:14.530 --> 01:20:16.760
I'm so close to
my expected value.

01:20:16.760 --> 01:20:20.110
So by having a distribution,
I can look up a trigger point

01:20:20.110 --> 01:20:20.730
and say--

01:20:20.730 --> 01:20:21.979
and I have to set the trigger.

01:20:21.979 --> 01:20:23.890
It has to be at
least 80% undervalue

01:20:23.890 --> 01:20:27.970
to kick in, which would be
about $124 to $122 for Apple.

01:20:27.970 --> 01:20:29.920
That becomes the
basis that I think

01:20:29.920 --> 01:20:33.280
about both buying and selling
is in terms of distributions,

01:20:33.280 --> 01:20:35.920
not in terms of point estimates.

01:20:35.920 --> 01:20:38.170
SPEAKER 1: So do we
have one live question

01:20:38.170 --> 01:20:38.920
from the audience?

01:20:38.920 --> 01:20:40.280
Yeah.

01:20:40.280 --> 01:20:43.072
AUDIENCE: So this
actually echoes--

01:20:43.072 --> 01:20:45.030
I guess you mentioned a
Monte Carlo simulation.

01:20:45.030 --> 01:20:46.990
I actually did a
Monte Carlo simulation

01:20:46.990 --> 01:20:48.650
for my PhD and
part of my feeling

01:20:48.650 --> 01:20:51.410
is just that all of
the assimilation--

01:20:51.410 --> 01:20:54.780
simulations, number
crunching, storytelling--

01:20:54.780 --> 01:20:57.600
all of this is assumptions
that goes into it, right?

01:20:57.600 --> 01:21:00.270
And it echoes the uncertainty,
the prediction part

01:21:00.270 --> 01:21:01.560
you're talking about.

01:21:01.560 --> 01:21:03.960
At the end of the
day, how do I know

01:21:03.960 --> 01:21:05.850
I made the right assumption?

01:21:05.850 --> 01:21:07.740
ASWATH DAMODARAN: The
word you used was know.

01:21:07.740 --> 01:21:09.827
You never know.

01:21:09.827 --> 01:21:11.410
And that's something
that-- and that's

01:21:11.410 --> 01:21:12.826
I said one of the
biggest problems

01:21:12.826 --> 01:21:15.450
that number crunchers have is
a psychological barrier you've

01:21:15.450 --> 01:21:19.560
got to overcome, which is we're
so used at the end of a math

01:21:19.560 --> 01:21:21.854
problem to checking
the answer and saying,

01:21:21.854 --> 01:21:22.770
I know I got it right.

01:21:22.770 --> 01:21:23.820
Look, I can check it.

01:21:23.820 --> 01:21:25.861
That's why accounting is
so much more comfortable

01:21:25.861 --> 01:21:27.030
to do than valuation, right?

01:21:27.030 --> 01:21:28.560
Balance sheets have to balance.

01:21:28.560 --> 01:21:30.077
It balanced, I'm done.

01:21:30.077 --> 01:21:32.410
The problem in valuation, you
get done with a valuation,

01:21:32.410 --> 01:21:34.576
and you look at it and say,
how do I know I'm right?

01:21:34.576 --> 01:21:37.060
I'll tell you the
answer, you don't.

01:21:37.060 --> 01:21:39.040
And you have to be OK with it.

01:21:39.040 --> 01:21:42.460
There is no confirmation
mechanism that I can offer you.

01:21:42.460 --> 01:21:44.800
That's why I used
the word faith.

01:21:44.800 --> 01:21:46.300
What's the essence of faith?

01:21:46.300 --> 01:21:48.730
Why do you go to church every
week or temple every week?

01:21:48.730 --> 01:21:52.420
It's because you have
faith that God exists.

01:21:52.420 --> 01:21:53.650
You say, prove it to me.

01:21:53.650 --> 01:21:55.300
I can prove it.

01:21:55.300 --> 01:21:56.950
The same thing
applies in investing.

01:21:56.950 --> 01:22:00.250
If you ask me, prove to
me that valuation works.

01:22:00.250 --> 01:22:02.590
I don't have proof,
I have faith.

01:22:02.590 --> 01:22:04.252
And I can't pass
that faith onto you.

01:22:04.252 --> 01:22:05.710
So when I teach my
valuation class,

01:22:05.710 --> 01:22:07.780
I tell people, at
the end of this class

01:22:07.780 --> 01:22:10.420
you have to decide for yourself
whether this works for you.

01:22:10.420 --> 01:22:13.660
I can teach you how
to value a company,

01:22:13.660 --> 01:22:15.430
but I can't give you faith.

01:22:15.430 --> 01:22:17.000
That's got to come from within.

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:19.157
Maybe you will develop
faith, maybe you will not.

01:22:19.157 --> 01:22:21.740
And if you don't develop faith,
it's not the end of the world.

01:22:21.740 --> 01:22:25.330
You can buy ETFs and index funds
and you'll be perfectly happy.

01:22:25.330 --> 01:22:27.500
And here is my
definition of faith,

01:22:27.500 --> 01:22:29.210
and it's going to sound morbid.

01:22:29.210 --> 01:22:31.540
I ask people who are
active investors,

01:22:31.540 --> 01:22:34.540
let's say you get to the age of
85, you're on your deathbed--

01:22:34.540 --> 01:22:36.700
I told you it was
a morbid thought--

01:22:36.700 --> 01:22:39.520
and I come to you
with some statistics.

01:22:39.520 --> 01:22:41.020
I say, look, over
the last 60 years,

01:22:41.020 --> 01:22:43.000
you've been doing valuation
and picking stocks

01:22:43.000 --> 01:22:45.300
and you made 8.13% a year.

01:22:45.300 --> 01:22:47.799
This is cruel and unusual to
somebody on their deathbed.

01:22:47.799 --> 01:22:49.340
And then I say, you
know what, if you

01:22:49.340 --> 01:22:51.090
had put your money in
ETFs and index funds

01:22:51.090 --> 01:22:55.110
over the last 60 years,
you would have made 8.22%.

01:22:55.110 --> 01:22:56.850
So you've spent 60
years of your life

01:22:56.850 --> 01:22:59.864
doing two hours of
research every night

01:22:59.864 --> 01:23:02.280
and you've essentially made
less money than you could have

01:23:02.280 --> 01:23:04.050
by just putting your money--

01:23:04.050 --> 01:23:06.120
would you be OK with it?

01:23:06.120 --> 01:23:08.070
And if your answer
is no, I tell people

01:23:08.070 --> 01:23:11.230
don't do active investing.

01:23:11.230 --> 01:23:12.100
I'd be OK with it.

01:23:12.100 --> 01:23:12.641
You know why?

01:23:12.641 --> 01:23:15.111
Because I enjoy
the process so much

01:23:15.111 --> 01:23:17.110
that even if at the end
of the game you told me,

01:23:17.110 --> 01:23:18.935
you're not going to make any
money off this, I would say,

01:23:18.935 --> 01:23:19.435
I'm OK.

01:23:19.435 --> 01:23:22.310
I've had lots of fun doing it.

01:23:22.310 --> 01:23:24.820
And that's, to me, part of
the reason the storytelling

01:23:24.820 --> 01:23:27.220
works is if I were just
crunching through spreadsheets,

01:23:27.220 --> 01:23:30.440
I would drive myself crazy.

01:23:30.440 --> 01:23:31.940
Because when you
do spreadsheets,

01:23:31.940 --> 01:23:32.990
you want affirmation--

01:23:32.990 --> 01:23:36.560
I did all this hard
work, I tortured myself.

01:23:36.560 --> 01:23:39.099
I need to be rewarded.

01:23:39.099 --> 01:23:41.390
And the market says, no, you
don't need to be rewarded.

01:23:41.390 --> 01:23:42.514
I'm going to take away 20%.

01:23:42.514 --> 01:23:44.060
And your neighbor,
who picks stock

01:23:44.060 --> 01:23:48.050
based on astrological
signs, is making millions.

01:23:48.050 --> 01:23:51.607
You say, this is so unfair.

01:23:51.607 --> 01:23:52.690
It's the way the world is.

01:23:52.690 --> 01:23:56.840
So unfortunately, there
is no way to know.

01:23:56.840 --> 01:24:01.700
But that's the part about faith
is it might come, it might not.

01:24:01.700 --> 01:24:05.870
But it's got to
come from within.

01:24:05.870 --> 01:24:07.970
AUDIENCE: And a small
quick follow-up question

01:24:07.970 --> 01:24:10.880
is, when we look at
valuation, how do we learn?

01:24:10.880 --> 01:24:13.490
For instance, if the
numbers come back

01:24:13.490 --> 01:24:15.320
agreeing with my
prediction, does it

01:24:15.320 --> 01:24:16.570
mean that I did a good job?

01:24:16.570 --> 01:24:19.170
How can I tell which part is
my work, which part is not?

01:24:19.170 --> 01:24:21.003
ASWATH DAMODARAN: Here's
what I tell myself.

01:24:21.003 --> 01:24:23.540
When I pick a stock and it
goes up, the first thing I say

01:24:23.540 --> 01:24:25.310
is, I got lucky.

01:24:25.310 --> 01:24:28.130
And then I say, OK, maybe
I did something on the side

01:24:28.130 --> 01:24:30.650
because luck is the dominant
paradigm in this business.

01:24:30.650 --> 01:24:34.190
There's so much stuff
that's out of your control

01:24:34.190 --> 01:24:37.310
that you really
can't do much about.

01:24:37.310 --> 01:24:39.590
And it helps you both on
the plus and the minus side.

01:24:39.590 --> 01:24:42.620
That's why I can be sanguine
about the stocks that go down

01:24:42.620 --> 01:24:44.522
is you can't be selective.

01:24:44.522 --> 01:24:45.980
And this is what
behavioral finance

01:24:45.980 --> 01:24:47.510
finds, when something
works you want

01:24:47.510 --> 01:24:49.880
to claim credit by yourself.

01:24:49.880 --> 01:24:52.010
When something doesn't,
what do you do?

01:24:52.010 --> 01:24:54.290
You blame the rest of the world.

01:24:54.290 --> 01:24:57.350
I mean, when I talk about taking
ownership of your investments,

01:24:57.350 --> 01:24:59.270
what I'm talking about
is taking ownership

01:24:59.270 --> 01:25:01.010
of both sides of
the investments.

01:25:01.010 --> 01:25:03.410
So we need to behave
exactly the same way

01:25:03.410 --> 01:25:04.571
when we win as we lose.

01:25:04.571 --> 01:25:05.820
And that's really tough to do.

01:25:05.820 --> 01:25:08.150
I have to force
myself to try to do it

01:25:08.150 --> 01:25:10.560
and it doesn't
come easily to me.

01:25:10.560 --> 01:25:14.610
SPEAKER 1: You've written
about Facebook, about Amazon,

01:25:14.610 --> 01:25:16.470
about Apple.

01:25:16.470 --> 01:25:18.300
Traditional value
investing has generally

01:25:18.300 --> 01:25:22.230
sort of put tech in a
certain light because

01:25:22.230 --> 01:25:25.080
of the risk of, I guess,
innovation disruption

01:25:25.080 --> 01:25:25.780
and whatnot.

01:25:25.780 --> 01:25:27.780
Do you think over time
that has changed and does

01:25:27.780 --> 01:25:30.702
value investing in
technology work well?

01:25:30.702 --> 01:25:32.160
ASWATH DAMODARAN:
It should change.

01:25:32.160 --> 01:25:33.840
And I think part
of the problem is

01:25:33.840 --> 01:25:36.270
we use the word tech
to capture this very

01:25:36.270 --> 01:25:37.920
diverse set of companies now.

01:25:37.920 --> 01:25:40.530
In the 1980s, if you
said tech, I'd have said,

01:25:40.530 --> 01:25:42.570
young, high growth, risky.

01:25:42.570 --> 01:25:44.790
Today when you say tech,
you're talking about 22%

01:25:44.790 --> 01:25:45.745
of the market.

01:25:45.745 --> 01:25:47.620
And you're talking about
companies that range

01:25:47.620 --> 01:25:49.770
the spectrum in life cycle.

01:25:49.770 --> 01:25:54.550
Intel is tech, but so is
Facebook and so is Snap.

01:25:54.550 --> 01:25:57.430
But what do they
share in common?

01:25:57.430 --> 01:26:01.180
One is a company that's I mean,
not quite the walking dead,

01:26:01.180 --> 01:26:03.010
but if you think
about Yahoo, so you

01:26:03.010 --> 01:26:06.730
can have walking dead tech
companies which are essentially

01:26:06.730 --> 01:26:09.820
looking towards the exit and
you can have companies growing.

01:26:09.820 --> 01:26:12.370
So a couple of years
ago, I actually

01:26:12.370 --> 01:26:17.230
took every tech company in the
US and I broke it down by age.

01:26:17.230 --> 01:26:21.140
It took the founding year and
I then looked at the metrics

01:26:21.140 --> 01:26:22.220
by age.

01:26:22.220 --> 01:26:25.909
And tech companies age
in what I call dog years.

01:26:25.909 --> 01:26:27.450
Do you know what I
mean by dog years?

01:26:27.450 --> 01:26:30.210
A 20-year-old tech company
is like a 140-year-old

01:26:30.210 --> 01:26:32.776
manufacturing company.

01:26:32.776 --> 01:26:34.400
Because the old man--
if you look at GM

01:26:34.400 --> 01:26:38.000
and how long GM and Ford took
to go from start-up to mature

01:26:38.000 --> 01:26:39.980
company, it took them 60 years.

01:26:39.980 --> 01:26:43.670
They stayed at that cash
cow status for about 30

01:26:43.670 --> 01:26:46.610
and then they went into
this long-term decline.

01:26:46.610 --> 01:26:49.424
A tech company, you look at it,
the growth that took 60 years,

01:26:49.424 --> 01:26:50.090
you do in eight.

01:26:50.090 --> 01:26:50.965
That's the good news.

01:26:50.965 --> 01:26:52.790
The bad news is you
don't get much of time

01:26:52.790 --> 01:26:55.060
to enjoy yourself as a cash cow.

01:26:55.060 --> 01:26:56.960
And then when you
start declining,

01:26:56.960 --> 01:26:58.954
the drop is precipitous.

01:26:58.954 --> 01:27:00.370
So if you think
about life cycles,

01:27:00.370 --> 01:27:02.889
the life cycle is a
much steeper lifestyle.

01:27:02.889 --> 01:27:04.430
So in tech companies,
I think we need

01:27:04.430 --> 01:27:06.950
to stop talking tech
as a collective space

01:27:06.950 --> 01:27:09.370
and think about some of the
best bargains in this market

01:27:09.370 --> 01:27:11.820
are in the old tech space.

01:27:11.820 --> 01:27:13.640
I'm talking the
Microsofts, the Intels.

01:27:13.640 --> 01:27:15.530
These are cash cows.

01:27:15.530 --> 01:27:16.380
Can be disrupted?

01:27:16.380 --> 01:27:16.880
Sure.

01:27:16.880 --> 01:27:19.940
So can GM, so can Ford, so can
Coca-Cola, so can McDonald's.

01:27:19.940 --> 01:27:22.520
What makes us think that just
because you have a consumer

01:27:22.520 --> 01:27:24.840
product company, I
can't disrupt you?

01:27:24.840 --> 01:27:27.210
Disruption is part
of this process.

01:27:27.210 --> 01:27:32.150
So to me, ignoring tech
because you feel it's too risky

01:27:32.150 --> 01:27:34.910
means that you're at
least 75 years old.

01:27:34.910 --> 01:27:37.670
Because we have
frames of references

01:27:37.670 --> 01:27:40.280
that come from the
1980s and the '90s

01:27:40.280 --> 01:27:42.290
that people are still
carrying through.

01:27:42.290 --> 01:27:46.130
I was happy when Warren
Buffett finally bought Apple

01:27:46.130 --> 01:27:50.117
because it's a small
step, but for a long time

01:27:50.117 --> 01:27:51.825
his view was, I don't
buy tech companies.

01:27:51.825 --> 01:27:53.241
In fact, his view
was, I don't buy

01:27:53.241 --> 01:27:55.580
anything I don't understand.

01:27:55.580 --> 01:27:57.500
And that basically
means 80% the world

01:27:57.500 --> 01:27:59.300
is going to go
outside the domain

01:27:59.300 --> 01:28:03.050
if that's your definition of not
being able to invest in things.

01:28:03.050 --> 01:28:04.820
So I think we need to
start breaking tech

01:28:04.820 --> 01:28:08.970
into old tech, middle
aged tech, and young tech.

01:28:08.970 --> 01:28:10.470
SPEAKER 1: This is
a little bit more

01:28:10.470 --> 01:28:13.422
into accounting because you've
written a lot about accounting.

01:28:13.422 --> 01:28:15.880
ASWATH DAMODARAN: I say very
nasty things about accounting,

01:28:15.880 --> 01:28:17.220
so hopefully I don't have
to say it [INAUDIBLE].

01:28:17.220 --> 01:28:18.360
SPEAKER 1: Well,
they still invite you

01:28:18.360 --> 01:28:20.880
to events and to give talks,
so I'm hoping all is well.

01:28:20.880 --> 01:28:23.520
But you've written about
reinvestment, growth and return

01:28:23.520 --> 01:28:25.470
on capital, and how
these are connected

01:28:25.470 --> 01:28:27.690
and you talked about that
in your talk as well.

01:28:27.690 --> 01:28:29.670
The question is
about definitions.

01:28:29.670 --> 01:28:32.890
When you think about
return on capital,

01:28:32.890 --> 01:28:37.650
capital can be defined as equity
plus debt minus excess cash.

01:28:37.650 --> 01:28:40.740
Some people define capital
as tangible capital

01:28:40.740 --> 01:28:44.460
that is used in
operating the business.

01:28:44.460 --> 01:28:48.030
What really drives compounding?

01:28:48.030 --> 01:28:49.800
Is it the tangible
capital and returns

01:28:49.800 --> 01:28:53.866
on tangible capital or is it
how you define it and sort of I

01:28:53.866 --> 01:28:56.490
guess what I'm asking is what is
the difference between the two

01:28:56.490 --> 01:28:58.366
approaches and how do
you make sense of that?

01:28:58.366 --> 01:28:59.740
ASWATH DAMODARAN:
The first thing

01:28:59.740 --> 01:29:01.659
is to stay away from the
accounting definition

01:29:01.659 --> 01:29:02.700
from all of these things.

01:29:02.700 --> 01:29:05.280
And let me explain what I
think about as reinvestment.

01:29:05.280 --> 01:29:06.664
You want to grow as a company.

01:29:06.664 --> 01:29:08.580
The question I want to
ask you is, what do you

01:29:08.580 --> 01:29:11.740
have to spend money on to grow?

01:29:11.740 --> 01:29:14.019
When I ask that of a
manufacturing company--

01:29:14.019 --> 01:29:16.560
what do you have to spend money
on, new factories, new plant,

01:29:16.560 --> 01:29:17.940
new equipment--

01:29:17.940 --> 01:29:20.719
and old time accounting
captures with the capex.

01:29:20.719 --> 01:29:22.260
You look at a
pharmaceutical company,

01:29:22.260 --> 01:29:24.520
what do you invest in to grow?

01:29:24.520 --> 01:29:26.210
R&amp;D.

01:29:26.210 --> 01:29:27.850
And what do
accountants do with it?

01:29:27.850 --> 01:29:29.410
Screw it up big time, right?

01:29:29.410 --> 01:29:31.660
They treat it as an
operating expense.

01:29:31.660 --> 01:29:33.959
And if I ask a
company like Google,

01:29:33.959 --> 01:29:35.500
what do you have to
reinvest to grow,

01:29:35.500 --> 01:29:37.930
you can already see the
accounting definitions are not

01:29:37.930 --> 01:29:40.360
going to capture what
you put money in to grow.

01:29:40.360 --> 01:29:42.820
You might have to grow by
buying young technologies

01:29:42.820 --> 01:29:45.740
because that's what you need
to bring into the space.

01:29:45.740 --> 01:29:47.230
So one of the
things we need to do

01:29:47.230 --> 01:29:50.634
is stop getting focused on what
does the accountant call capex.

01:29:50.634 --> 01:29:52.300
Because that's not
going to capture what

01:29:52.300 --> 01:29:54.820
I want to call capex at
a company like Google.

01:29:54.820 --> 01:29:57.790
Because that's the only way for
me to be rational in the way

01:29:57.790 --> 01:29:59.719
I think about valuing
these companies.

01:29:59.719 --> 01:30:01.510
If you're a consulting
company, what do you

01:30:01.510 --> 01:30:03.820
have to invest in to grow?

01:30:03.820 --> 01:30:05.110
Human capital.

01:30:05.110 --> 01:30:07.780
So those recruiting and
training expenses that you have,

01:30:07.780 --> 01:30:10.912
some of that at least should
be treated like capex.

01:30:10.912 --> 01:30:13.180
So my definition of
capex is not going

01:30:13.180 --> 01:30:15.340
to match an accountant's
definition of capex

01:30:15.340 --> 01:30:18.232
because my definition of capex
is driven by how quickly do

01:30:18.232 --> 01:30:20.440
you want to grow and what
do you need to put money in

01:30:20.440 --> 01:30:21.231
to get that growth?

01:30:23.540 --> 01:30:25.040
SPEAKER 1: Same
thing about capital,

01:30:25.040 --> 01:30:26.040
like tangible capital versus--

01:30:26.040 --> 01:30:26.530
ASWATH DAMODARAN: Same thing.

01:30:26.530 --> 01:30:28.150
Once you make that definition.

01:30:28.150 --> 01:30:30.170
My invested capital at
a company like Google

01:30:30.170 --> 01:30:32.799
will require me to
capitalize R&amp;D, right?

01:30:32.799 --> 01:30:34.340
Because if you put
money in R&amp;D and I

01:30:34.340 --> 01:30:36.370
do what the accountants
do, it will never shop as--

01:30:36.370 --> 01:30:38.600
SPEAKER 1: What about goodwill
and non-operating assets

01:30:38.600 --> 01:30:39.140
and stuff like that?

01:30:39.140 --> 01:30:40.970
ASWATH DAMODARAN: Goodwill
is kind of a useless area.

01:30:40.970 --> 01:30:43.002
It's the most dangerous
variable ever created

01:30:43.002 --> 01:30:44.960
because it shows up when
you do an acquisitions

01:30:44.960 --> 01:30:46.629
and accountants--
it's a plug variable.

01:30:46.629 --> 01:30:48.170
SPEAKER 1: So you
would not count it.

01:30:48.170 --> 01:30:48.860
ASWATH DAMODARAN:
I wouldn't count it

01:30:48.860 --> 01:30:50.890
as part of invested capital,
simply because you could

01:30:50.890 --> 01:30:52.140
consistently keep [INAUDIBLE].

01:30:52.140 --> 01:30:56.030
Because goodwill captures future
growth, it captures stupidity,

01:30:56.030 --> 01:30:57.710
it captures premiums
you're paying.

01:30:57.710 --> 01:31:00.930
It captures everything you do
over and above that book value.

01:31:00.930 --> 01:31:03.530
So to me goodwill is
a non-asset, right?

01:31:03.530 --> 01:31:04.460
SPEAKER 1: OK.

01:31:04.460 --> 01:31:06.140
Thank you so much
for humoring us

01:31:06.140 --> 01:31:08.540
with our questions and your
valuable time and talk.

01:31:08.540 --> 01:31:09.140
[APPLAUSE]

01:31:09.140 --> 01:31:11.290
Thank you so much.

